ory, the book probes the Portuguese and African contributions to the brotherhoods in Part One. Part Two traces the changes and continuities within the organizations from the early eighteenth century to the end of the Brazilian Empire, and the book concludes in Part Three with discussion of the twentieth-century brotherhoods and narratives of the participants in brotherhood festivals in the 1990s. In a larger sense, the book serves as a case study through which readers can examine the strategies that Afro-Brazilians used to create viable communities in order to confront the asymmetry of power inherent in the slave societies of the Americas and their economic and social marginalization in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aBlack peoplezBrazilzMinas GeraisxReligion. 0aBlackszBrazilzMinas GeraisxReligion. 0aBrotherhoodszBrazilzMinas GeraisxHistory. 0aRosary, Our Lady of thexCultzBrazilzMinas GeraisxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aAfrican diaspora Our Lady of the Rosary.  aAfro-Brazilians Carribean Studies.  aBrazil.  aElizabeth W. Kiddy.  aMinas Gerais.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271032320?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271032320423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271032320/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK